ined in the headers class.\\n     */\\n    Class<?> headersClass() default void.class;\\n\\n    /**\\n     * The name of the field to get or the name of the method without parameters to invoke to get the name of the\\n     * headers defined in an enum.\\n     * <p/>\\n     * Only took into account if and only if the class defined as {@code headersClass} is an enum.\\n     * <p/>\\n     * For example, assuming that {@code SomeEnum} has been configured as the {@code headersClass} of a given component,\\n     * since the name of the header is actually the value of the field {@code headerName}, the element\\n     * {@code headersNameProvider} should be set to {@code \\\"headerName\\\"} to get the expected header names.\\n     *\\n     * <pre>\\n     * <code>\\n     *\\n     * public enum SomeEnum {\\n     *    {@literal @}Metadata\\n     *     FOO(\\\"fooKey\\\");\\n     *\\n     *     public final String headerName;\\n     *\\n     *     SomeEnum(final String str) {\\n     *         this.headerName = str;\\n     *     }\\n     * }\\n     * </code>\\n     * </pre>\\n     */\\n    String headersNameProvider() default \\\"\\\";\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777865521965}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.camel:spi-annotations:4.0.0/fix-javac-fail/pi-generation-2026-05-04T03-32-13-234091Z.log:862:[thinking] I need to edit my import to include the right categories and assert that the endpoint's category contains exactly `Category.TESTING` and `Category.CORE`. I'll start with a default empty array and add an annotation for the category. I should use `assertThat(endpoint.category()).containsExactly(...)`. For cases where there's a default, `assertThat(endpoint.category()).isEmpty()` works for arrays of objects. I'll also need to import `org.apache.camel.Category` to get everything in order.\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.camel:spi-annotations:4.0.0/fix-javac-fail/pi-generation-2026-05-04T03-32-13-234091Z.log:866:[tool-call] delta {\"path\":\"tests/s